Label: AL rdfs:label@en
Definition: AL IAO:0000115@en

Label: distributed identifier
Definition: An identifier issued by more than one authority
Example: postal codes are assigned by each country

Label: two part identifier
Definition: An identifier which has a centrally registered component and a locally administered component
Example: DOI have two parts, an identifier of the issuer, and then an identifier of the object as dubbed by the issuer

Label: multi-part identifier
Definition: An idenitifer whose parts are dubbed by multiple authorities
Example: An internet protocol 4 number is assigned in parts.

Label: crossref funder identifier
Definition: An identifier assigned by CrossRef to an organization which has funded a project resulting in a published work
Example: The CrossRef ID for the University of Florida is 100007698.  When authors cite the univeristy as a funder of their work, CrossRef uses this number to identify the university

Label: amazon standard identification number
Definition: A 10-character alphanumeric unique identifier assigned by Amazon.com and its partners for product identification within the Amazon organization.

Label: coden
Definition: A six character, alphanumeric bibliographic code, that provides concise, unique and unambiguous identification of the titles of periodicals and non-serial publications from all subject areas.

Label: dbpedia identifier
Definition: A URL used by DBpedia to identify an entity
Example: The DBpedia URL for the football player Cristiano Ronaldo is http://dbpedia.org/resource/Cristiano_Ronaldo

Label: european article numbering-uniform code council 13
Definition: A 13 digit number, often encoded into bar codes for the purpose of identifying an entity item for sale
Example: EAN-13 are commonly found on the wrapping of a package of a good bought in a store.

Label: electronic international standard serial number
Definition: The e-ISSN (or eISSN) is a standard label for "Electronic ISSN", the ISSN for the electronic media (online) version of a serial.
Example: The eISSN of the journal PLOS One is 1932-6203

Label: eracommons identifier
Definition: An identifier used by the National Institues of Health in the United States to identify researchers for the purpose of research administration

Label: global research organization identifier
Definition: An identifier assigned and managed by Digital Science for the purpose of denoting research organizations
Example: The ISBN-13 for Native Son, by Richard Wright, Harper Perennial, Reissued 2005 is 978-0-06-083756-3

Label: international standard book number 10
Definition: The International Standard Book Number (ISBN 10) is a 10-digit numeric commercial book identifier which is intended to be unique.[a][b] Publishers purchase ISBNs from an affiliate of the International ISBN Agency.

Label: international standard book number 13
Definition: The International Standard Book Number (ISBN 13) is a 13 digit numeric commercial book identifier which is intended to be unique.[a][b] Publishers purchase ISBNs from an affiliate of the International ISBN Agency.

Label: isi researcher identifier
Definition: An identifier assigned by Clarivate to researchers to associate them with their works

Label: international standard name identifier
Definition: An identifier for persons and organizations which may be assigned by matching algorithms based on records provided by publishers

Label: International standard serial number
Definition: An International Standard Serial Number (ISSN) is an eight-digit serial number used to uniquely identify a serial publication, such as a magazine.[

Label: library of congress control number
Definition: The Library of Congress Control Number (LCCN) is a serially based system of numbering cataloged records in the Library of Congress, in the United States.

Label: nih manuscript id
Definition: An identifier assigned by the National Institutes of Health during manuscript submission for compliance with NIH open access policies

Label: online computer library center control number
Definition: An OCLC number is a unique control number given to all bibliographic records in the WorldCat catalog.

Label: open researcher and contributor identifier
Definition: Open Researcher and Contributor ID is an alphanumeric code (ORCID iD) to uniquely identify authors and contributors of scholarly communication

Label: pubmed central identification number
Definition: The PMCID (PubMed Central identifier), also known as the PMC reference number, is a bibliographic identifier for the PubMed Central database, much like the PMID is the bibliographic identifier for the PubMed database.

Label: pubmed identifier
Definition: A PMID (PubMed identifier or PubMed unique identifier) is a unique integer value, starting at 1, assigned to each PubMed record.

Label: research organization registry identifier
Definition: An identifier assigned by ROR to research organizations in the world

Label: scopus author identifier
Definition: The Scopus Author Identifier distinguishes among similar names by assigning each author in Scopus a unique number and grouping all of the documents written by that author.

Label: serial item and contribution identifier
Definition: The Serial Item and Contribution Identifier (SICI) was a code (ANSI/NISO standard Z39.56-1996 [R2002]) used to uniquely identify specific volumes, articles or other identifiable parts of a serial.

Label: universal product code
Definition: The Universal Product Code (UPC; redundantly: UPC code) is a barcode symbology that is widely used in the United States, Canada, Europe, Australia, New Zealand, and other countries for tracking trade items in stores.

Label: united states patent number
Definition: A patent number is an identifier assigned by a patent office and is used often in a patent search. The format depends on the issuing office, the type of patent, and when the patent was issued.

Label: wikidata q number
Definition: QID (or Q number) is the unique identifier of a data item on Wikidata, comprising the letter "Q" followed by one or more digits.

Label: drivers license number
Definition: An identifier assigned to the license issued to a person who has been qualified to drive a vehicle by an authority

Label: health care provider identifier
Definition: An identifier issued to a person as a result of their being licensed as a health care provider by an authority
Example: In the US, the National Provider Identifier (NPI) is a health care provider ID

Label: local award identifier
Definition: An identifier assigned to an award by an organizaton which received it

Label: local grant identifier
Definition: An identifier assigned to a grant by the organization which was awarded the grant

Label: local project identifier
Definition: An identifier assigned by an organization to one of its projects

Label: local person identifier
Definition: An identifier assigned by an organization to a person affiliated with the organization

Label: local information content entity identifier
Definition: An identifier assigned to an ice by a repository in which it is held

Label: passport number
Definition: An identifier issued by a national authority to a passport document intended to associate that document with a specific human being

Label: report identifier
Definition: An identifier assigned to a report.  From the BIBO ontology.
Editors Note: do we need this?  Does not appear to be in the current BIBO ontology.

Label: sponsor award identifier
Definition: An identfier assigned to an award by its sponsor

Label: internet protocol address
Definition: An Internet Protocol address (IP address) is a numerical label assigned to each device connected to a computer network that uses the Internet Protocol for communication.

Label: media access control address
Definition: A media access control address (MAC address) is a unique identifier assigned to a network interface controller (NIC) for use as a network address in communications within a network segment.

Label: archival resource key
Definition: An Archival Resource Key (ARK) is a Uniform Resource Identifier (URI)[1] that is a multi-purpose persistent identifier for information objects of any type.

Label: digital object identifier
Definition: A digital object identifier (DOI) is a persistent identifier or handle used to identify objects uniquely, standardized by the International Organization for Standardization (ISO).

Label: uniform resource identifier
Definition: A Uniform Resource Identifier (URI) is a unique sequence of characters that identifies a logical or physical resource used by web technologies.

Label: uniform resource locator
Definition: A Uniform Resource Locator (URL), colloquially termed a web address,[1] is a reference to a web resource that specifies its location on a computer network and a mechanism for retrieving it. A URL is a specific type of Uniform Resource Identifier (URI),[2][3] although many people use the two terms interchangeably.

Label: internationalized resource identifier
Definition: The Internationalized Resource Identifier (IRI) is an internet protocol standard which builds on the Uniform Resource Identifier (URI) protocol by greatly expanding the set of permitted characters.
Example: The IRI https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/_____ (Ancient Greek) can be resolved to a URI https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E1%BF%AC%CF%8C%CE%B4%CE%BF%CF%82 which is a URL (identifies a location on the web)

Label: accession number
Definition: In libraries, art galleries, museums and archives, an accession number is a unique identifier assigned to, and achieving initial control of, each acquisition. Assignment of accession numbers typically occurs at the point of accessioning or cataloging.

Label: handle
Definition: The Handle System is the Corporation for National Research Initiatives's proprietary registry assigning persistent identifiers, or handles, to information resources, and for resolving "those handles into the information necessary to locate, access, and otherwise make use of the resources"
Editors Note: How to represent handles as URL?  Same question fro DOI.  Is this a quality of the identifier?

Label: uniform resource name
Definition: A Uniform Resource Name (URN) is a Uniform Resource Identifier (URI) that uses the urn scheme. URNs are globally unique persistent identifiers assigned within defined namespaces so they will be available for a long period of time, even after the resource which they identify ceases to exist or becomes unavailable.

Label: scopus eid
Definition: A unique academic work identifier assigned in the scopus bibliographic database

Label: web of science uniform identifier
Definition: A unique academic work identifier assigned in the web of science bibliographic database

Label: arxiv identifier
Definition: A unique academic work identifier assigned in the arxiv bibliographic database

Label: bibcode
Definition: The bibcode (also known as the refcode) is a compact identifier used by several astronomical data systems to uniquely specify literature references.

Label: purl
Definition: A persistent uniform resource locator (PURL) is a uniform resource locator (URL) (i.e., location-based uniform resource identifier or URI) that is used to redirect to the location of the requested web resource.

Label: open citation identifier
Definition: The Open Citation Identifier (OCI) is a globally unique persistent identifier for bibliographic citations, created and maintained by OpenCitations, and this page provides a resolution service that takes an OCI and returns information about that citation.

Label: digital author identifier
Definition: In the Dutch research system, the Digital Author Identifier (DAI) system assigns a unique number to all academic authors as a form of authority control.

Label: virtual international authority file identifier
Definition: The Virtual International Authority File (VIAF) is an international authority file. It is a joint project of several national libraries and operated by the Online Computer Library Center (OCLC)

Label: open identifier
Definition: OpenID is an open standard and decentralized authentication protocol.

Label: ringgold identifier
Definition: The Ringgold Identifier is a unique numerical identifier applied to organizations in the scholarly supply chain

Label: research activity identifier
Definition: RAiD is a Persistent IDentifier for research projects organized by the Australian Research Data Commons

Label: github gist identifier
Definition: A gist is a shareable file with a unique, peristent URL that you can edit, clone, and fork on GitHub. The gist URL is its identifier.

Label: secure hash algorithm-1 hash
Definition: In cryptography, SHA-1 (Secure Hash Algorithm 1) is a cryptographic hash function which takes an input and produces a 160-bit (20-byte) hash value known as a message digest Ð typically rendered as a hexadecimal number, 40 digits long.

Label: research resource identifier
Definition: Research Resource Identifiers are ID numbers assigned to help researchers cite key resources (antibodies, model organisms and software projects) in the biomedical literature to improve transparency of research methods.

Label: international geo sample number
Definition: The International Geo Sample Number or IGSN is a sample identification code of typically nine characters.
Definition Source: The International Geo Sample Number or IGSN is a sample identification code of typically nine characters.
